name: treatment of municipal solid waste, unsanitary landfill, dry infiltration class (100mm) | municipal solid waste | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/19105/documentation

This dataset represents the activity of waste disposal of 'municipal solid waste' in a unsanitary landfill. Recommended use of this dataset: unsanitary landfilling of mixed municipal waste in a dry water infiltration class location. Not suitable to represent any single specific waste material, like plastics, paper, cardboard. If your waste is a specific mixture of waste materials, inventory the respective waste materials individually. Inventoried waste contains several fractions: 21% paper; 8% Mixed cardboard; 15% plastics; 3% laminated materials; 2% laminated packaging, e.g. drinks cartons; 3% combined goods e.g.  diapers; 3% glass; 2% textiles; 8% minerals; 9% natural products; 22% compostable material; 2.65% inert metals; 1% volatile metals; 0.0065% batteries; 0.34% electronic goods. Waste composition (wet, in ppmw): gross heating value 13.27 MJ/kg; net heating value 11.74 MJ/kg; H2O 228830; O 257060; H 48250; C 334230; S 1119; N 3123.8; P 893.79; B 7.1933; Cl 6866.2; Br 13.552; F 56.358; I 0.0121; Ag 0.714; As 0.62521; Ba 149.04; Cd 11.748; Co 1.3453; Cr 315.21; Cu 1212.8; Hg 1.4424; Mn 259.36; Mo 1.9551; Ni 107.38; Pb 502.42; Sb 22.564; Se 0.31969; Sn 73.44; V 9.2147; Zn 1311.2; Be na; Sc na; Sr na; Ti na; Tl na; W na; Si 48510; Fe 29996; Ca 14062; Al 12420; K 2059.7; Mg 3377.7; Na 5143.9. Share of carbon in initial waste that is biogenic 60.4%. Share of metals in waste not oxidised and bulk-recyclable (exclude very small or thin parts) Iron: 60.03%; Alu: 17.81%; Copper: 72.83%. Overall degradability of waste during 100 years: 18.73%. Degradability of composing waste fractions: paper: 27%; Mixed cardboard: 32.4%; plastics: 1%; laminated materials: 18%; laminated packaging, e.g. drinks cartons: 18%; combined goods e.g.  diapers: 18%; glass: 0%; textiles: 12%; minerals: 0%; natural products: 27%; compostable material: 27%; inert metals: 10%; volatile metals: 0%; batteries: 0%; electronic goods: 0%; . 0.04597 kg waste mass remains in the landfill even after the long term period.

The activity starts with the waste being available at the gate of the treatment facility. Collection and transportation of the waste to the treatment plant is not included.

The activity ends with the waste being treated and waste-specific emissions from the landfill are released to air via landfill gas, and to water via leachate.
category: E:Water supply; sewerage, waste management and remediation activities/38:Waste collection, treatment and disposal activities; materials recovery/382:Waste treatment and disposal/3821:Treatment and disposal of non-hazardous waste

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: This dataset represents a landfill of 'infiltration class 2 dry'. Landfill site with mean annual temperature (MAT) of 8 degC, mean annual precipitation (MAP) of 550 mm/year, and net infiltration of 100 mm/year. Temperature at site can result in permafrost conditions, which slows down water flow by a factor of (alpha t) 0.999. Total climate adjustments with alpha pt of 0.999. The leachate percolating through the landfill has an average residence time of 37.5 years.;Reference for climatic parameters: Doka, G., 2018, Inventory parameters for regionalised waste disposal mixes
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: This is an inventory for an unsanitary, sub-controlled landfill for municipal solid waste. Ultimate average landfill height is 15 meters. Operation phase duration is 25 years. The total, waste-specific raw landfill gas mass produced in the landfill is 0.1106 kg. The total CH4 mass in the raw landfill gas is 0.05454 kg. Percentage of landfill gas directly emitted is 100w%. Leachate of the landfill is not treated, but emitted untreated. Based on average waste composition and chosen climate data the end of carbonate phase is estimated to be reached 16577 years after waste deposition.
